    <id>http://arxiv.org/abs/2605.15045v1</id>
    <title>Can a late-time cosmological model based on baby universe absorption explain the z-variation of w?</title>
    <updated>2026-05-14T16:38:22Z</updated>
    <link href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2605.15045v1" rel="alternate" type="text/html"/>
    <link href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2605.15045v1" rel="related" type="application/pdf" title="pdf"/>
    <summary>We point out that a simple late-time cosmological model where our Universe can absorb "baby universes" explains the exponential expansion of our universe without the need of a cosmological constant and leads to a z-dependence of the parameter w(z) in the equation of state. In this model w(z) is less than -1 for z sufficiently large.</summary>
